- content_for :page_title, 'Under the Hood'

%h1.ribbon Under the Hood
%p OpenShift is made of many different Open Source software components working in harmony to power your apps.  The list below describes each component and links to the public GitHub repository.

%section.row
  .span6
    %dl.larger
      %dt.headline= link_to "Crank Case", "#{openshift_github_url}/crank_case", :class => "external", :target => "_blank"
      %dd User Management Component
      %dt.headline= link_to "Gear Changer", "#{openshift_github_url}/gear_changer", :class => "external", :target => "_blank"
      %dd Short description to come
      %dt.headline= link_to "RHC", "#{openshift_github_url}/os-client-tools", :class => "external", :target => "_blank"
      %dd Command-line client tools
      %dt.headline= link_to "StickShift", "#{openshift_github_url}/openshift/stickshift", :class => "external", :target => "_blank"
      %dd Provides API
      %dt.headline= link_to "SwingShift", "#{openshift_github_url}/swingshift", :class => "external", :target => "_blank"
      %dd Provides user authentication
      %dt.headline= link_to "Uplift", "#{openshift_github_url}/uplift", :class => "external", :target => "_blank"
      %dd DNS Management component

      %p
        %em Coming soon &mdash; the OpenShift web console

  .span5.info-ribbon
    %h2 Test Drive
    %p.larger
      Get all the components preconfigured in a bootable disk image.
    - if logged_in?
      - download = Download.find('remix')
      = take_action download_path(download), download.name
    - else
      = take_action download_index_path, "Start Download"
    %p
      Once you got it, you can
      = link_to "run it as a virtual guest", "#"
      ,
      = link_to "boot it from a LiveCD", "#"
      , or
      = link_to "boot it from a USB stick", "#"
    %p
      Then, we suggest you read the
      = link_to "live image documentation", "#"
      for instructions on what to do after you boot.
    .well
      %h4 Important Information
      %p
        This image contains software from Fedora 16.  Corresponding source packages for such software are available at
        = link_to "http://koji.fedoraproject.org/koji", "http://koji.fedoraproject.org/koji"

